Copilot said: Absolutely! Here is a clear, safe guide
Absolutely! Here is a clear, safe guide to fix your Unity project’s Git problems and set up a clean Unity repo:

Step 1: Add or Fix .gitignore
Why:
.gitignore tells git to ignore/untrack big/auto-generated Unity folders like Library/, Temp/, Build/, etc.
You should NEVER add or commit the Library/ folder to Git!

How:

In the root of your Unity project (the folder with Assets/ and Library/), create a file named .gitignore if it doesn't exist.
Paste this (the official Unity template):
gitignore
[Ll]ibrary/
[Tt]emp/
[Bb]uild/
[Bb]uilds/
[Ll]ogs/
[Mm]emoryCaptures/
UserSettings/
obj/
.vs/
ExportedObj/
.consulo/
*.svd
*.user
*.planner
*.sublime-workspace

# Uncomment this line if you wish to ignore the Asset Store tools plugin
# [Aa]ssets/AssetStoreTools*

# Mono Auto Generated Files
*.pidb
*.booproj
*.sln
*.userprefs

# Unity3D generated meta files
*.pidb.meta

# Unity3D Generated File On Crash Reports
sysinfo.txt

# Builds
*.apk
*.unitypackage

# Force all files in the 'StreamingAssets' directory to be treated as binary by Git.
# Useful if you store binary files in that directory, such as images, videos, etc.
# You can remove this if you want git to handle text files normally
StreamingAssets/**

# Ignore JetBrains Rider files
.idea/
*.sln.iml